P2P Instant File Transfer Platform

1. Executive Summary
Product Name: TunnelDrop (working title)
Vision: Build the world's fastest file transfer service by eliminating server-side storage entirely and creating direct peer-to-peer connections between devices.
Core Value Proposition:

Zero upload wait time—downloads begin instantly
No file size limits
Complete privacy (no server storage)
Works across all devices and platforms
Local network discovery for same-location transfers

Target Launch: MVP in 8-12 weeks

2. Problem Statement
Current Pain Points

Double Latency: Traditional services (WeTransfer, Google Drive) require full upload before download can begin
Artificial Limits: File size caps (2GB-100GB) based on business models
Privacy Concerns: Files stored on third-party servers, subject to scanning/monitoring
Cross-Platform Friction: AirDrop only works Apple-to-Apple; alternatives are clunky
Account Barriers: Most services require sign-up, reducing spontaneous sharing

User Scenarios

Hostel/College: Students sharing large files (movies, games, project files) within same building
Office: Colleagues transferring large datasets without email/Slack limits
Events/Conferences: Quick file sharing between attendees
Cross-device: Personal transfers between own devices without cloud middleman


3. Solution Overview
Core Technology
WebRTC Data Channels for direct browser-to-browser communication with:

STUN/TURN servers for NAT traversal (minimal infrastructure)
Signaling server for connection handshake only
No file data touches our servers

Key Differentiators

Instant Start: Receiver begins downloading while sender is still "uploading"
True Unlimited: No file size restrictions (limited only by device storage)
Privacy-First: Zero-knowledge architecture
Universal Compatibility: Works on any device with a modern browser
Local Discovery: Automatic peer detection on same network


4. Feature Requirements
4.1 MVP Features (Phase 1)
A. Core Transfer Flow
Priority: P0 (Must Have)
User Story: As a sender, I want to share a file with minimal friction.
Requirements:

User lands on homepage, no login required
Click/tap "Send File" button
Select file(s) via file picker or drag-and-drop
System generates 4-digit numeric code (0000-9999)
Display QR code encoding the connection URL
Show waiting state: "Waiting for receiver..."
Once connected, show transfer progress bar
Transfer begins immediately (streaming)
Completion notification with option to send another file

Technical Specs:

Support files up to 100GB (initial soft cap for testing)
Chunk size: 16KB-64KB (optimized for WebRTC)
Transfer speed display (MB/s)
Automatic reconnection on connection drop
Connection timeout: 5 minutes if no receiver joins


B. Receiver Flow
Priority: P0
User Story: As a receiver, I want to access files with a simple code.
Requirements:

User lands on homepage
Click/tap "Receive File" button
Enter 4-digit code OR scan QR code
Show sender's device name/browser info (e.g., "Chrome on Windows")
Display file name, size, and estimated transfer time
"Accept" or "Decline" button
If accepted, auto-download or show "Save As" dialog (browser-dependent)
Real-time progress indicator
Completion notification

Technical Specs:

WebRTC connection established within 2-3 seconds
Fallback to TURN relay if direct P2P fails
Resume support for interrupted transfers (Phase 2 consideration)
Multiple file support (send as batch or zip)


C. Signaling Infrastructure
Priority: P0
Requirements:

Lightweight WebSocket signaling server
Room-based architecture (code = room ID)
ICE candidate exchange
Connection state management
Automatic room cleanup after transfer or timeout

Technical Specs:

Signaling server handles only metadata (no file data)
Max 2 peers per room for MVP
Room expiry: 10 minutes after creation or 2 minutes after transfer completion
Server stores zero persistent data


4.2 Phase 2 Features
D. Local Network Discovery ("Local Drop")
Priority: P1 (High Value)
User Story: As a user in a shared location, I want to see nearby devices for instant sharing.
Requirements:

"Nearby Devices" tab on homepage
Display list of other users on same local network
Each user shown as avatar/device name with online indicator
Click to initiate direct transfer (no code needed)
Privacy toggle: "Visible to nearby devices" (on by default)

Technical Specs:

Use WebRTC + local network multicast/broadcast or shared signaling room
Detect common private IP range (192.168.x.x, 10.x.x.x)
Update peer list every 5-10 seconds
Anonymous IDs with user-customizable display names


E. Multi-Peer Transfers
Priority: P2
Requirements:

One sender, multiple receivers (1-to-N)
Sender generates single code/QR
Each receiver gets independent stream
Bandwidth split evenly among receivers


F. Transfer History (Client-Side Only)
Priority: P2
Requirements:

Browser localStorage keeps last 10 transfers
Display: filename, size, timestamp, peer info
"Send Again" quick action
Clear history button
Never sent to server


4.3 Future Enhancements (Phase 3+)

Desktop Apps: Electron-based native apps for Windows/Mac/Linux
Mobile Apps: React Native or native iOS/Android for background transfers
Transfer Resume: Handle reconnections without restarting
Folder Sharing: Send entire directories
Text/Link Sharing: Quick clipboard sharing via same mechanism
Password Protection: Optional 4-digit PIN on top of code
Encrypted Transfers: End-to-end encryption (WebRTC already encrypts, but add user-controlled keys)


5. User Experience & Design
5.1 Design Principles

Radical Simplicity: Every screen should have one primary action
Speed Perception: Show activity immediately (no blank states)
Trust Signals: Clearly communicate privacy/security
Universal Design: Works on 4" phone and 27" desktop equally well

5.2 Visual Direction

Minimalist: Single-page app, clean typography, lots of white space
Speed Metaphors: Visual "tunnel" animation during transfer
Dark Mode: Optional, appealing to privacy-conscious users
Responsive: Mobile-first, scales up

