6. Technical Architecture
6.1 Tech Stack
Frontend:

Framework: React 18+ (or Svelte for smaller bundle)
WebRTC Library: PeerJS or simple-peer
Styling: Tailwind CSS
State Management: Zustand or React Context
QR Generation: qrcode.react

Backend (Minimal):

Signaling Server: Node.js + Socket.io or ws library
Hosting: Cloudflare Workers or Railway.app (cheap, globally distributed)
STUN Server: Public STUN (Google's stun:stun.l.google.com:19302)
TURN Server: Coturn (self-hosted) or Twilio's TURN service (fallback)

Infrastructure:

CDN: Cloudflare for static assets
Domain: Short, memorable (e.g., tunneldrop.io)
SSL: Let's Encrypt (required for WebRTC)

6.2 Data Flow
┌─────────┐                    ┌─────────┐
│ Sender  │                    │Receiver │
└────┬────┘                    └────┬────┘
     │                              │
     │  1. Request room             │
     ├──────────────────────────────┤
     │        Signaling Server      │
     │  2. Return code: 4829        │
     │◄─────────────────────────────┤
     │                              │
     │                              │
     │  3. Enter code 4829          │
     │      ┌───────────────────────┤
     │      │  4. Join room 4829    │
     │      ├───────────────────────┤
     │      │  Signaling Server     │
     │      │  5. Exchange ICE      │
     ├──────┼───────────────────────┤
     │◄─────┴───────────────────────┤
     │                              │
     │  6. Direct P2P Connection    │
     │        (WebRTC)              │
     ├─────────────────────────────►│
     │      File Data Stream        │
     ├─────────────────────────────►│
     │                              │
6.3 WebRTC Connection Logic
javascript// Pseudo-code

// Sender
const peer = new SimplePeer({ initiator: true });
peer.on('signal', data => {
  socket.emit('signal', { room: code, signal: data });
});
peer.on('connect', () => {
  // Stream file in chunks
  streamFile(file, peer);
});

// Receiver
const peer = new SimplePeer({ initiator: false });
socket.on('signal', data => {
  peer.signal(data);
});
peer.on('data', chunk => {
  // Reconstruct file
  appendChunk(chunk);
});
6.4 Scalability Considerations

Signaling Server: Handles only handshakes, not file data. Can scale horizontally.
TURN Relay: Only used when P2P fails (~10-20% of connections). Bandwidth cost is main concern.
Cost Projection:

90% of transfers: $0 (pure P2P)
10% via TURN: ~$0.05/GB (Twilio pricing)
If 10,000 transfers/day @ 1GB avg, 1000 via TURN = $50/day = $1500/month



Mitigation:

Encourage local network use (no TURN needed)
Rate limit: 5 transfers/hour per IP
Premium tier for heavy users (future)


7. Privacy & Security
7.1 Privacy Features
Zero-Knowledge Architecture:

Files never stored on servers
Signaling server sees only: timestamp, room codes, IP addresses (temp)
No analytics on file contents

Data Retention:

Room codes: Deleted after 10 minutes or transfer completion
Logs: 24-hour rolling window (for debugging only)
No user accounts = no user data

7.2 Security Measures
In Transit:

WebRTC is encrypted by default (DTLS-SRTP)
Signaling over WSS (WebSocket Secure)

Code Security:

4-digit codes (10,000 combinations) expire quickly (5 min)
Rate limiting on code attempts (10/minute per IP)

Future:

Optional password protection
SHA-256 file verification (sender/receiver compare hashes)

7.3 Legal/Compliance
GDPR/Privacy:

No personal data collected
Privacy policy: "We don't see your files, period."

DMCA/Abuse:

No ability to monitor content (by design)
Terms of Service: "Don't share illegal content"
Abuse contact: If notified, can block IP/device (temporary)

Jurisdiction:

US-based legal entity (simpler compliance)


